TY  - JOUR
T1  - Voter Behavior in Union Certification Elections: A Longitudinal Study
AU  - Davy, Jeanette A.
AU  - Shipper, Frank
Y1  - 1993/02/01
PY  - 1993
DA  - 1993/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256518
DO  - 10.5465/256518
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 187
EP  - 199
VL  - 36
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This study assessed the relations among social pressures favoring unions, job satisfaction, perceptions of union instrumentality, and individuals'voter behavior using covariance structure analysis. Job satisfaction and union instrumentality were measured prior to and following union certification elections. Results indicate social pressure was the strongest predictor of voter behavior, having a direct effect as well as mediated effects through satisfaction and commitment. Only voter behavior directly affected satisfaction and commitment after elections, suggesting significant cognitive readjustment took place among individuals.
AB  - This study assessed the relations among social pressures favoring unions, job satisfaction, perceptions of union instrumentality, and individuals'voter behavior using covariance structure analysis. Job satisfaction and union instrumentality were measured prior to and following union certification elections. Results indicate social pressure was the strongest predictor of voter behavior, having a direct effect as well as mediated effects through satisfaction and commitment. Only voter behavior directly affected satisfaction and commitment after elections, suggesting significant cognitive readjustment took place among individuals.
