TY  - JOUR
T1  - Managing Russian Factory Workers: The Impact of U.S.–Based Behavioral and Participative Techniques
AU  - Welsh, Dianne H. B.
AU  - Luthans, Fred
AU  - Sommer, Steven M.
Y1  - 1993/02/01
PY  - 1993
DA  - 1993/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256512
DO  - 10.5465/256512
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 58
EP  - 79
VL  - 36
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The new internationalization of the field of management has produced growing concern as to whether theories and techniques largely developed in the United States apply to other cultures. A within-subjects experimental design was used to analyze the impacts that three popular and successful techniques used in U.S. studies had on the performance of workers in the largest textile factory in the Russian republic of the former Soviet Union. Two techniques, providing extrinsic rewards and behavioral management, had significant, positive effects, but a participative technique led to a decrease in performance.
AB  - The new internationalization of the field of management has produced growing concern as to whether theories and techniques largely developed in the United States apply to other cultures. A within-subjects experimental design was used to analyze the impacts that three popular and successful techniques used in U.S. studies had on the performance of workers in the largest textile factory in the Russian republic of the former Soviet Union. Two techniques, providing extrinsic rewards and behavioral management, had significant, positive effects, but a participative technique led to a decrease in performance.
